For this exercise, we are going to use the already cleaned data set from the palmerpenguins package again. Thus, load all packages you need first.

library(palmerpenguins)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

Create a scatter plot using the two numerical variables you picked in the last exercise to fit a linear regression model. Plot the data (for all species) using point colors that refer to the island the data was collected. Use a solid triangle as point shape.

color_palette <- c(Biscoe = "#d28f40", Dream = "#61aac5", Torgersen = "#a62b29")

penguins$island <- factor(penguins$island, levels = c("Biscoe", "Dream", "Torgersen"))

plot(penguins$flipper_length_mm, penguins$bill_length_mm, col = color_palette[penguins$island], pch = 17, 
xlab = "Flipper length [mm]", ylab = "Bill length [mm]")

legend("bottomright", legend = c("Biscoe", "Dream", "Torgersen"), 
       col = color_palette, pch = 17)

Now fit the linear regression model again, and add the regression line to the figure.

plot(penguins$flipper_length_mm, penguins$bill_length_mm, col = color_palette[penguins$island], pch = 17, 
xlab = "Flipper length [mm]", ylab = "Bill length [mm]")

lm_model <- lm(bill_length_mm ~ flipper_length_mm, data = penguins)
abline(lm_model)

lm_island <- dplyr::group_by(penguins, island) %>% 
  dplyr::group_split() %>% 
  purrr::map(lm, formula = bill_length_mm ~ flipper_length_mm) %>% 
  purrr::set_names(c("Biscoe", "Dream", "Torgersen"))

purrr::walk2(lm_island, names(lm_island), function(x,y) abline(x, col = color_palette[y]))

Create a boxplot of the difference between islands of the body size. Try to also add the raw data points to the boxplot.

boxplot(body_mass_g ~ island, data = penguins, xlab = "Island", ylab = "Body mass [g]")
points(x = jitter(as.numeric(penguins$island)), y = penguins$body_mass_g)
